 Referring now to Figs. 1 and 2, the keyboard consists of a cylindrical shell It with slots il cut therein. A plurality of key levers II are rotatably mounted on a central shaft II and are moved in the slots II to specifled points along the circumference of the shell in to enter digits into the accumulator. A gear section M (Fig. 2) is provided as an integral Par of each key lever I for meshing with the accumulator numeral wheels. To insure more accurate placing of the key levers, a detent I, mounted upon each of said levers with the customary sprlng-pin-slot combination, is used in cooperation with an internal star wheel, segment ll. 4 
 This form of keyboard is similar in many respects to commercial cash registers and is well known in the art. 
 Toward the rear of the machine an accumulator shaft ll extends transversely for the entire width of the machine and is supported at each end by an irregular flat support ll (see Fig. which rocks on a shaft II Journaled near the The shaft l1 extends through the supports it a short distance so as to engage cam levers II in cam slots 22. Manual movement is imparted to levers 2| by means of a pair of handles 23 which extend upward through slots in the keyboard face. The cam slots 22 are so constructed as to move a series of numeral wheels 24 into engagement with the sear sectors II when the handles 23 are moved toward the front of the machine (see Fig. 6). When the. handles are moved to the rear, the shaft II is cammed back to the position sh wn in Pig. 2, the numeral wheels are then 1' of the gear sector ll, but are held securely by a series of detents 2!. 
 The detents 2! are fixedly mounted by means of two rods II and 84 and held in spaced relation by a plurality of sleeves 35. One detent is provided for each numeral wheel 24. 
The accumulator (see Figs. 2, 4, 6, '1, 8, 9, 
and is creep-carry, the main parts of which are well known in the art and have been described in several patents. These parts include in each the nine-toothed numeral wheel 24, a,oouplin g disc ll, an eccentrically mounted or floating gear 31, and an eccentric bearing 38 on-a sleeve ll. To these are added a ten-toothed resultant gear 0 and a snail cam 4| which assist in the operation of the reading a and clearing mechanism. 
 As previously stated the geared sectors II, which enter the amounts, mesh with the ninetoothed numeral wheels II. To each of these wheels is secured a coupling disc 18 which has 10 three holes 42 cut therein to cooperate wth a series of three pins 43 which are attached to the eccentric gear 31. 
 The floating gear 31 (Fig. 4) has nine notches on its periphery and these mesh with ten pins ll (acting as internal gear teeth) which are acoured to the snail cam ll. Since the tooth spacing is the same for both gears, the floating gear 31 is free to move around within the ten tooth gear under the control of the eccentric 2 bearing 38, gaining one tooth during each revolution of the sleeve ll. 
 The resultant gear I is secured to the snail cam 4i. However, in order to make room for certain parts of the reading mechanism a spacer 25 I is interposed between them when they are riveted together. The assembly consisting of the cam 4i, spacer l5 and gear ll, constitutu the resultant wheel, which is fast on the right-hand end of the sleeve 46 which passes through the 80 Sear 24, disc 38 and gear 31 of the next hkher denomination and has the eccentric ll fast on its lefthand end. In the units order the sleeve II is fixedly anchored to the frame member ll as indicated at the left in Fig. 11. The resultant 35 gear in any one order is also pinned to the sleeve 48 in the same order so that, when the gear 40 makes one complete revolution, the eccentric bearing 30 causes the floating gear 81 in the next higher order, in cooperation with the w internal gear formed by the pins 44, 'to rotate the higher order shall cam ll one-tenth of a revolution. This is the usual means of carry in creepcarry accumulators. 
 The numeral wheel 24 has only nine teeth but it must be turned'a total of ten teeth to cause a full rotation of the resultant gear ll. This may easily be understood by. considering the coupling between the two wheels. The nulmral wheel flissecuredto thecouplingdiscllwhieh is coupled to the floating gear I! by the pin and hole combination "-43. The floating gear I! has nine teeth while the internal gear has ten teeth 44. As long as the eccentric is held immovable, a ten to nine ratio in rotation is introduced at this point. As the pins 44 are attached to the snail cam which is riveted to the resultant wheel ll, there is always a ten to nine or one and one-ninth ratio between the numeral and resultant wheels, This mode of operation is similar to that of prior creep-carry mechanisms. 
 Above the accumulator, and in a position which will permit easy observation, is a series of dial indicators 4! rotatably mounted on a shaft ll. Each dial indicator has a cylindrical surface on which is printed digits from 0 to 9, inclusive, and each dial is secured to a ten toothed gear ll 1 from which it receives its motion. 
